Queue can be both an abstract data type (ADT) and a data structure, depending on how it is implemented. 
As an ADT, Queue provides a set of operations for adding elements to the beginning and end of the queue, removing elements from the middle of the queue, and checking whether the queue is empty. These operations are defined in terms of a hypothetical implementation of the queue, rather than being specific to any particular implementation. 
For example, if we define a Queue as follows:
```
class Queue {
    private array elements;

    public function Queue(size: number): void {
        this.elements = new Array(size);
    }

    public function enqueue(element: any): void {
        this.elements[this.length] = element;
        this.length++;
    }

    public function dequeue(): any {
        return this.elements[0];
        // Note: This implementation assumes that the queue is not empty.
    }

    public function peek(): any {
        return this.elements[0];
    }

    public function isEmpty(): boolean {
        return this.length === 0;
    }
}
```
Then, we can use this Queue class to implement different types of queues such as linked list queue, circular buffer queue, etc.
On the other hand, as a data structure, a queue is typically used to store and retrieve elements in a First-In-First-Out (FIFO) order. It consists of a sequence of nodes, where each node contains a value and may have additional information about its position in the queue. The last node in the queue points to null, indicating the end of the queue. 
To add an element to the queue, we simply append a new node containing the element to the end of the existing queue. To remove an element from the queue, we start at the first node and compare the element with the one currently pointed to by the next pointer. If they match, we update the next pointers of both nodes and discard the matched element. Otherwise, we move to the next node. We continue until we reach the end of the queue or find a non-matching element. 
Both implementations allow us to perform basic operations like insertion and deletion of elements, which makes them useful for various applications.

